national_strategy_info:
The specific Belgian ‘Ocean Science strategy’ emerges from the federal and competent regional (Flemish) policies that have a specific bearing on the Belgian part of the North Sea. As such, it has not been formulated as a separate document.

At federal level: 
- Ocean Science is included in the different research funding mechanisms, where projects responding to (or relevant to) the needs of marine economic and environmental policies (including spatial management) for the Belgian North Sea can be fostered.

BELSPO, the Belgian Science Policy Office, is one of the main actors in support of scientific research in Belgium.  It has coordinated and implemented research programmes focused on the marine environment for 45 years. Those research programmes aim at further increase our knowledge of the marine environment and stimulate a sustainable management and exploitation of it. BELSPO manages the research programmes in support of the policy with regard to sustainable development, actions to address climate change, biodiversity, energy, health, mobility and the information of society. Of particular importance for the marine research field is the programme BRAIN-be (Belgian Research Action through Interdisciplinary Networks, renewed in 2018). Furthermore, marine research using remote sensing techniques is financed by the STEREO programme on the use of remote sensing.

As an EU Member State, Belgium participates in the EU maritime policy and its research policy. Under these policies, the following initiatives and frameworks merit specific mention:

-	The Horizon 2020 funding programme, being replaced by ‘Horizon Europe’ from 2021;
-	The Joint Programming Initiative ‘Healthy and Productive Seas and Oceans’ (JPI Oceans) with its ‘Strategic Research and Innovation Agenda’ to which Belgium subscribes: http://jpi-oceans.eu/strategy
-	Other research funding coordination mechanisms, such as the relevant co-funding mechanisms (ERA-NETs and other).
Within Belgium, Flanders’ marine science community (and beyond) receives strategic support services by the Flanders Marine Institute, VLIZ. This institute provides infrastructures, data and information, managed by VLIZ with the support of the Flemish Department of Economy, Science and Innovation. VLIZ itself has a research framework: http://www.vliz.be/imisdocs/publications/312430.pdf

efforts_keep_graduates_info:
Il y a eu création d’une formation de Master en océanographie physique initiée par l’IRHOB et exécuté par l’Université d’Abomey-Calavi
Il y a eu des formations de Master en hydrobiologie à l’Université d’Abomey-Calavi; L’IRHOB est associé à cette formation.
Actuellement il y a des difficultés, au plan national pour le recrutement des cadres dans tous les domaines. Il y a des promesses pour le recrutement des cadres en sciences d la mer. 
Il y a eu des efforts pour le recrutement dans le domaine de la pêche.

national_strategy_info:
Pas exclusivement mais dispose d’une loi-cadre sur la pêche, la loi du code de la marine marchande et la loi-cadre sur l’environnement qui traitent des problèmes liés à l’environnement marin et la pêche.
-	Loi-cadre sur l’environnement : http://bch-cbd.naturalsciences.be/benin/implementation/legislation/loicadre.pdf
-	Loi-cadre sur la pêche et l’aquaculture au Bénin : http://ajape-asso.over-blog.com/2015/05/loi-cadre-n-2014-19-du-07-aout-2014-relative-a-la-peche-et-a-l-aquaculture-en-republique-du-benin.html
-	Code de la Marine Marchande : https://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/docs/MONOGRAPH/88026/100542/F240680817/BEN-2010-L-88026.pdf
-	l’IRHOB dispose :
o	d’un plan de suivi des paramètres physico-chimiques de l’eau (marine et saumâtre). 
o	d’un plan de suivi de quelques espèces marines d’intérêt commercial dont les cétacés.
o	d’un plan de suivi de l’érosion côtière par des mesures mensuelles des lignes de côtes.

efforts_keep_graduates_info:
Los mayores esfuerzos son realizados por el MESCYT a través de FONDOCYT; se aplican incentivos salariales  por el monto de  US$3,000.00/mes a científicos que desarrollan  proyectos de investigación. Desde su inicio el programa  FONDOCYT  ha asistido a 8 científicos en las  ciencias marinas. 
Existen programas de intercambio que realizan algunas instituciones estatales con otras  homologas   en países con los cuales se mantienen relaciones diplomáticas. Estos intercambios  son gestionados a través de las legaciones correspondientes.

efforts_keep_graduates_info: To gain scientific understanding of the earth system (the atmosphere, ocean, solid earth, biosphere) as well as to study the interactions between its components and their response to the natural and human induced changes, several programmes have been launched. In order to cater to the enormous requirement of skilled manpower in the field of Earth System Sciences three training schools have been established. The main objective was to create a pool of trained and dedicated earth system and climate system scientists with in-depth hands-on expertise on physical processes of the land, ocean, atmosphere, biosphere and cryosphere with special emphasis on modeling.

collaboration_info:
NOAA NCEI shares earth environmental data with several international organizations, national data centers, world data centers and services, international data management offices. These include data and information on weather and climate, space weather, atmosphere, and oceans. In addition, NCEI operates the World Data Service for Oceanography (https://www.nodc.noaa.gov/worlddatacenter/). For illustration, below we list a few examples of ocean data that NCEI shares:

has_observation_programmes_info:
Argo Profiling Floats - These floats provide the subsurface measurements of ocean temperature and salinity that are critical inputs to global sea level change and upper ocean heat content, as well as fundamental global subsurface ocean information important for understanding distribution and movement of fish. Twenty-two nations plus the European Union currently maintain 3,500 floats. Development of deep diving Argo floats is underway with deployment of test floats anticipated in FY 2014. http://www.argo.ucsd.edu/ 
Biogeochemical Argo Floats - Biogeochemical (BGC) Argo floats provide subsurface measurements of 6 bgc parameters (oxygen, nitrate, pH, irradiance, backscatter and chlorophyll) that will allow for improved monitoring of marine ecosystems and ocean health, as well as advances in earth system modeling capabilities. Currently 16 nations contribute to BGC Argo (345 floats) with floats that have at least one biogeochemical sensor. The U.S. National Science Foundation sponsors the largest BGC Argo effort in the world, with support from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.

Surface Drifting Buoys - Sea surface temperature is an important ocean variable for the global heat, water, and carbon cycles and is critical to climate, ecosystem, and weather research. NOAA strives to maintain a global array of 1,250 surface drifting buoys with 14 international partners. This array is used to calibrate satellite observations and reduce errors in global measurement of this critical ocean variable. http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/keynotes/keynotes_0814_oceanbouys.html 

Tide Gauge Stations - Sea level rise is one of the most immediate impacts of climate change with the potential to affect coastal ecosystems, communities, and economies. Tide gauge stations also contribute to weather research through improved storm surge models. NOAA, in cooperation with 66 nations, is implementing the Global Climate Observing System sea level reference network of 170 international tide gauge stations to measure sea level 
change at the coast and to calibrate the satellite altimeter measurements of the deep ocean. GPS-enhanced tide gauge stations will enable more accurate measurements of sea level change. https://tidesandcurrents.noaa.gov/stations.html?type=Water+Levels 

Tropical Moored Buoys - Earth’s tropics are the ocean’s major source for heat exchange with the atmosphere. Together with international partners, NOAA is working to instrument all three tropical oceans - the Pacific Tropical Atmosphere Ocean (TAO) Array; Atlantic (PIRATA); and Indian (RAMA) Oceans - for continuous real-time measurement of ocean-atmosphere exchanges that affect the way our climate varies from year to year. https://www.pmel.noaa.gov/gtmba/pmel-theme/pacific-ocean-tao 
 
Ocean Reference Stations - NOAA, in cooperation with international partners, is implementing a sparse global network of high-quality ocean reference station (ORS) moorings for accurate long-term climate records in key ocean regions. The ORS surface and subsurface measurements are a cornerstone of the documentation of long-term changes in the ocean and provide “ground truth” for improving forecast models. https://www.ngs.noaa.gov/CORS/ 

Ocean Carbon Networks - Projecting decadal to centennial global climate change is closely linked to assumptions about feedbacks between the ocean and atmosphere related to sequestering of carbon in the ocean and additional input of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere. NOAA, in cooperation with the National Science Foundation and international partners, is implementing an ongoing ocean carbon inventory surveying the globe once every ten years and augmenting those observations with a network of moored buoys and instrument systems installed aboard volunteer observing ships.

Dedicated Ships - The United States Federal Oceanographic Fleet is a critical national infrastructure that supports government agency and academic oceanographic operations across a broad spectrum of national needs such as Science and Technology (Research), including Earth Systems Science and Polar, Resource Management (Survey), including Living Marine Resource Surveys and Hydrographic Surveys. Ships provide access to the world’s oceans and United States Coastal waters, and enable data collection and research for thousands of stakeholders from academia, government, and the public sector. The Unites States had an oceanographic fleet of XX vessels at the end of 2018.  The Fleet is composed of ships greater than 40 meters (130 feet) in length that are owned and operated or leased by the Federal government, along with those State or institutionally owned ships.

CoastWatch/OceanWatch - This data portal provides near-real time ocean satellite data products in support of aquatic monitoring efforts (e.g., harmful algal bloom bulletins and marine oil spill response). http://coastwatch.noaa.gov/cwn/index.html

Coral Reef Watch - Monitors coral reef ecosystems by identifying areas at risk for coral bleaching through the utilization of satellite data. http://coralreefwatch.noaa.gov/satellite/index.php

Marine Optical Buoy (MOBY) - MOBY is an autonomous optical buoy used for ocean color satellite vicarious calibration efforts. http://www.star.nesdis.noaa.gov/sod/moby/papers/papers/SPIE%206744A-56.pdf. Data source:  http://www.star.nesdis.noaa.gov/sod/moby/ 

Research Moored Array for African-Asian-Australian Monsoon Analysis and Prediction (RAMA) - A system of moored buoys collecting meteorological and oceanographic data in the Indian Ocean which greatly enhances the predictability of monsoons and other climatic events (Source: http://www.pmel.noaa.gov/tao/ )

Tropical Atmosphere Ocean (TAO) – Real-time data from moored ocean buoys in the Pacific Ocean for improved detection, understanding and prediction of El Niño and La Niña. (Source: http://www.pmel.noaa.gov/tao/

Prediction and Research Moored Array in the Atlantic (PIRATA) - a program designed to study ocean-atmosphere interactions in the tropical Atlantic that affect regional climate variability on seasonal, interannual and longer time scales. (Source: http://www.pmel.noaa.gov/pirata/)

Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study (BATS) – A time series established to answer questions about the ocean by collecting data on important physical (hydrographic), chemical, and biological parameters throughout the water column at multiple sites within the Sargasso Sea (Source: http://www.bios.edu/research/projects/bats/)

The Hawaii Ocean Time-Series (HOTS) – A program of repeat observations of the hydrography, chemistry and biology of the water column, stationed north of Oahu. (Source: http://hahana.soest.hawaii.edu/hot/)

A long-Term Oligotrophic Habitat Assessment (Station ALOHA) – A study designed to better   understand the oceanographic processes in the North Pacific. http://aco-ssds.soest.hawaii.edu/ALOHA/ 

Deep-Ocean Assessment and Reporting of Tsunamis (DART) -  To ensure early detection of tsunamis and to acquire data critical to real-time forecasts, NOAA has placed Deep-ocean Assessment and Reporting of Tsunami (DART®) stations at sites in regions with a history of generating destructive tsunamis (source: http://www.ndbc.noaa.gov/dart/dart.shtml )
 
The US Integrated Ocean Observing System (IOOS) -  A primary focus of U.S. IOOS is integration of, and expedited access to, ocean observation data for improved decision making. The Data Management and Communication (DMAC) subsystem of U.S. IOOS serves as a central mechanism for integrating all existing and projected data sources. https://ioos.noaa.gov/ 

The U.S. Ocean Acidification Program and the Global Ocean Acidification Observing Network (GOA-ON) - The U.S. Ocean Acidification Program supports 19 buoys in coastal and open ocean waters to capture ocean chemistry and track ocean acidification. It also conducts yearly research cruises and is pioneering the use of wave gliders to collect data. The Program is heavily involved in the GOA-ON, which coordinates global activities to monitor ocean acidification and its impacts. https://oceanacidification.noaa.gov/, http://goa-on.org/

efforts_support_female_graduates_info:
*The programs listed below are not only advertised to female graduates and scientists in ocean science related positions; however, these programs encourage applications from underrepresented groups, including women, minorities, persons with disabilities, and veterans, in order to broaden and diversify those participating in science and engineering.
National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship Program (NSFGRFP) - The NSF Graduate Research Fellowship Program recognizes and supports outstanding graduate students in NSF-supported science, technology, engineering, and mathematics disciplines who are pursuing research-based Master's and doctoral degrees at accredited United States institutions. https://www.nsfgrfp.org/
Dr. Nancy Foster Scholarship Program - The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's (NOAA) Dr. Nancy Foster Scholarship Program recognizes outstanding scholarship and encourages independent graduate level research -- particularly by female and minority students -- in NOAA mission-related sciences of oceanography, marine biology and maritime archaeology, including all science, engineering and resource management of ocean and coastal areas https://fosterscholars.noaa.gov/
